<P>
Monsoon floods leave millions homeless, stranded, hungry in north
India, Bangladesh
</P>
<P>
LUCKNOW, India -- Helicopters drop food to almost 2 million
hungry and frightened villagers perched on rooftops in India as
torrents of water from monsoon rains push the death toll in India
and neighboring Bangladesh to almost 200, officials say.  ASIA-
MONSOON FLOODS. Developing. By Biswajeet Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
Rocket blasts off carrying Mars lander; should reach red planet's
Arctic Circle next year
</P>
<P>
CAPE CANAVERAL, Florida -- A robotic dirt-and-ice digger blasts
off on a 422 million-mile (679 million-kilometer) journey to Mars
that NASA hopes will culminate next May in the first ever landing
within the red planet's Arctic Circle. If all goes to plan, the
Phoenix Mars Lander will spend three months scooping up soil and
ice, analyzing the samples in search of conditions favorable for
life.  MARS. Moved. By Marcia Dunn. AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
EUROPE:
</P>
<P>
Farmers wait and fear after foot-and-mouth disease returns to
England
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British scientists worked Saturday to trace the source
of a foot-and-mouth disease outbreak on an English farm and
authorities imposed a nationwide ban on moving livestock in a bid
to stop the spread of the highly infectious virus that devastated
the farming industry in 2001. The government said the European
Union would ban livestock exports from Britain in response to the
outbreak.  Developing. By Jill Lawless. AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
Parliament dominated by Islamic grouping opens in Turkey
</P>
<P>
ANKARA, Turkey -- Turkey's parliament, dominated by an Islamic
group of parties, opens as lawmakers take the oath of office.
Developing. By Selcan Hacaoglu. AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
MIDDLE EAST:
</P>
<P>
Iraqi lawmakers greet soccer heros
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi lawmakers clap and cheer for the country's Asian
Cup soccer champs at a rare gathering during parliament's summer
recess. Politicians pose for photos with the players at a hotel
in Baghdad's heavily fortified Green Zone, but the celebration
was closed to all but Iraq's political elite, with tight security
preventing regular citizens from welcoming their soccer heroes
home in person. Developing. By Bushra Juhi. AP Photos.
</P>
<P>
AFRICA:
</P>
<P>
SOMALIA: 1 civilian killed in grenade attack on funeral
procession in Somali capital
</P>
<P>
MOGADISHU, Somalia -- An unidentified man threw a grenade at a
funeral procession, killing one person and wounding three others
in the Somali capital, a witness said.  Upcoming. By Mohamed Olad
Hassan.
</P>
<P>
Gasoline stations run dry and tempers fray as strike bites
</P>
<P>
CAPE TOWN, South Africa -- Gasoline stations run dry, and long
lines form at the few that still have supplies, as a week-old
strike by fuel sector workers grips many parts of South Africa.
Johannesburg is hardest hit, with panic buying by motorists
before the weekend worsening the situation.  AFRICA-STRIKE.
Developing. By Clare Nullis. AP Photo.
</P>
<P>
ASIA:
</P>
<P>
Car bomb in northwest Pakistan kills 6, wounds 31; militants
clash with troops elsewhere
</P>
<P>
PESHAWAR, Pakistan -- Militants detonate a car bomb at a busy bus
station in northwestern Pakistan, killing six people and wounding
31 others, officials say. Elsewhere in the region, four soldiers
and 10 militants are killed during a checkpoint shootout.
ATTACKS. Developing. By Riaz Khan.
</P>
<P>
American tasked with spreading Hiroshima legacy
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Sixty-two years later, the memory of the atomic bombing
of Hiroshima still holds such a grip on Japan that its defense
minister has had to resign simply for suggesting the attack was
"unavoidable." Now, in a sign of changing times, the task of
keeping spreading Hiroshima's message to the world has been
entrusted to an American, a citizen of the country that dropped
the bomb on Aug. 6, 1945. LEGACY. Moved. By Cathy Bussewitz. AP
Photos.
</P>
<P>
NORTH AMERICA:
</P>
<P>
US House of Representatives to consider Bush terrorism spy bill
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The White House is halfway to its goal of winning
expanded powers to eavesdrop on suspected foreign terrorists.
Senate Democrats reluctantly agreed to pass a bill to update the
1978 Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act. The House is to
consider it Saturday after rejecting a Democratic alternative the
night before.  Developing. By Lara Jakes Jordan.
</P>
<P>
WITH:
</P>
<P>
-- LAW. WASHINGTON -- Bush signs legislation that intensifies
anti-terrorism effort in U.S., shifting money to high-risk areas
and expanding scrutiny of air and sea cargo. Moved.
</P>
<P>
Death toll from U.S. bridge collapse could end up far lower than
envisioned
</P>
<P>
MINNEAPOLIS -- When a bridge suddenly crashed into the
Mississippi River during rush hour, it seemed like a recipe for a
massive death count. But the city's fire chief says it appears
that relatively few lives were lost in the disaster.  COLLAPSE.
Moved. By Sharon Cohen and Adam Geller. AP Photos. AP Graphics
MINN BRIDGE 3D, MINN BRIDGE BEFORE AFTER, MINNEAPOLIS BRIDGES.
</P>
<P>
Jury finds U.S. soldier guilty of rape, murder in slaying of 14
-year-old Iraqi girl and her family
</P>
<P>
FORT CAMPBELL, Kentucky -- A military jury finds a soldier guilty
of rape and murder in the slayings of a 14-year-old Iraqi girl
and her family. Sentencing is Saturday.  SLAYING. Developing. By
Ryan Lenz.
</P>
<P>
WITH:
</P>
<P>
-- SLAYING. FORT CAMPBELL, Kentucky -- Military jury deliberating
in case of soldier charged with rape and murder in Iraq. Moved.
